Discrete Time & Continious Time Event History Analysis

Sergej Kaiser

3/05/2017

The document shows some of the visualizations, which I created for the course Event history analysis. The focus of event history anlysis is to predict the time-to-event outcomes, such as e.g.birth of a child.
The first visualizations show the discrete time analysis of the chance of a third birth. The continious time analysis is about general mortality risk.

Discrete Time models

The first visualization displays the (lack of) fit of various specifications of the baseline hazard of the chance of a third birth.
We model the chance of the third birth using a logistic regression. For each model the outcome is the birth of a third child and the dependent variable is time (const linear, quadratic, etc.).

Continious Event History

Kaplan Meier cumulative hazard

The Kaplan-Meier estimator is a simple non-parametric method to obtain an estimate of the survival curve from time-to-event data. It can be used with both discrete and continious time-to-event data. Here our focus is to model the outcome general mortality by educational categories.

Kaplan-Meier with covariate education

Cox regression with covariate education

We continue to study the outcome general mortality risk. The following graph shows the recovered non-parametric cummulative hazard of general mortality by educational according. We obtained the cum. hazard function from a cox regression.
The cox regression is a tool to build predictive models for continious time-to-event data (see: e.g.SPSS Manual 22). It allows to study the effect of a covariate on the outcome without assumptions about the hazard function.
